<p><b>Thomas Sowell</b> (born June 30, 1930), is an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Economist" title="Economist">economist</a>, social commentator, and author of dozens of books. He often writes from an economically <a href="/wiki/Laissez-faire" title="Laissez-faire">laissez-faire</a> perspective. He is currently a senior <a href="/wiki/Fellow" title="Fellow">fellow</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Hoover_Institution" title="Hoover Institution">Hoover Institution</a> at <a href="/wiki/Stanford_University" title="Stanford University">Stanford University</a>. In 1990, he won the <a href="/wiki/Francis_Boyer_Award" title="Francis Boyer Award">Francis Boyer Award</a>, presented by the <a href="/wiki/American_Enterprise_Institute" title="American Enterprise Institute">American Enterprise Institute</a>. In 2002 he was awarded the <a href="/wiki/National_Humanities_Medal" title="National Humanities Medal">National Humanities Medal</a> for prolific scholarship melding <a href="/wiki/History" title="History">history</a>, <a href="/wiki/Economics" title="Economics">economics</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Political_science" title="Political science">political science</a>.</p>
